'''
1. Architectural Blueprint
The original Transformer (from the paper "Attention Is All You Need") relies on an Encoder-Decoder structure.
The Core Flow:
1.	Input Representation: Words $\rightarrow$ Input Embeddings + Positional Encodings.
2.	Encoder Stack: Learns representation of the source sequence.
3.	Decoder Stack: Learns to generate the target sequence autoregressively using self-attention and cross-attention (attending to the encoder's output).
4.	Linear & Softmax Layer: Maps the decoder's output to the vocabulary probability distribution.
3. Detailed Explanation of Terms
To defend this code, you must explain these exact terms:
•	d_model: The structural dimensionality of the network. Every token's embedding and the output of every major sub-layer has this exact size (usually $512$ in base models). 
•	Query ($Q$), Key ($K$), Value ($V$): * Query: What the current token is looking for.
o	Key: What other tokens offer in terms of information.
o	Value: The actual informational payload content.
•	Scaled Dot-Product Attention: The mathematical formulation used to match Queries and Keys:
$$\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \text{softmax}\left(\frac{QK^T}{\sqrt{d_k}}\right)V$$
•	Multi-Head Attention (MHA): Instead of calculating one attention map, we split the $d_{\text{model}}$ into $h$ heads (each of size $d_k = d_{\text{model}} / h$). This allows the model to attend to different parts of the sentence simultaneously (e.g., syntactic vs. semantic relationships). 
•	Positional Encoding (PE): Since Transformers process all inputs in parallel (unlike sequential RNNs), they have no native sense of word order. PE injects relative/absolute sequence positions using sine and cosine functions of varying frequencies. 
•	Layer Normalization (LayerNorm): Normalizes activations across features for each individual training sample, stabilizing training. This differs from BatchNorm, which normalizes across the batch dimension.
•	Causal / Subsequence Masking: In the decoder, we must prevent the model from "looking into the future" when training. A lower-triangular matrix filled with $-\infty$ (or $0$ boolean values) is added to the attention scores to mask future tokens. 
